content.problemStatement:
The modulus operator (`%`) in C++ is an arithmetic operator that calculates the remainder when one integer is divided by another. It’s a powerful tool for many programming tasks involving remainder checks, cyclic patterns, and modular arithmetic. If the dividend is negative, the remainder will also be negative.

**Syntax:**
```cpp
dataType remainder = dividend % divisor;
```
- The `dividend` (on the left-hand side of %) is the number to be divided.
- The `divisor` (on the right-hand side of %) is the number you divide by.
- The `remainder` is stored on the left-hand side.
---

**Example:**
```cpp
#include 
using namespace std;

int main() {

    int dividend1 = 10;  // The number to be divided (Positive) 
    int divisor1 = 3;    // The number to divide by (Positive)

    // Modulus operator (%) returns the remainder after division
    int remainder1 = dividend1 % divisor1;

    // Print the remainder 
    cout << "Remainder1: " << remainder1 << endl; 

    int dividend2 = -10;  // The number to be divided (Negative) 
    int divisor2 = 3;     // The number to divide by (Positive)

    // Modulus with a negative dividend → result keeps the sign of the dividend
    int remainder2 = dividend2 % divisor2;

    // Print the remainder 
    cout << "Remainder2: " << remainder2 << endl;  

    int dividend3 = -10;  // The number to be divided (Negative) 
    int divisor3 = -3;    // The number to divide by (Negative)

    // Modulus with negative dividend and divisor → result still keeps the sign of the dividend
    // In C++, the sign of the result is always the same as the dividend
    int remainder3 = dividend3 % divisor3;

    // Print the remainder 
    cout << "Remainder3: " << remainder3 << endl;  

    // remainder2 and remainder3 will always be the same as long as the dividend is the same, because the result of the modulus operator (%) in C++ always has the same sign as the dividend, regardless of the sign of the divisor.

    return 0;
}

```

**Expected Output:**
```default
Remainder1: 1
Remainder2: -1
Remainder3: -1
```

